(571, 2, '2016-01-27 13:04:09', '2016-01-27 07:19:09', '[:en]<h3>Project Description</h3>\r\nOn 5 December, 2015, seven months after the April 25 and May 12 earthquakes, ArtWorks! <em>Sangai Khelaun</em> arrived at Gatlang, Rasuwa with a team of fifteen educators and artists—visual and language artists, dancers, and musicians.\r\n\r\nWe arrived in a majority Tamang village of over 500 households where all the homes were destroyed by the earthquake, and except for a few, people are living in tents in the surrounding fields.  For three days, our team conducted art workshops from ECD to Class 5 at Nepal Rastriya Secondary School’s Temporary Learning Centres.  The school has a little less than three hundred children from ECD to Class 10.  Through the work with the teachers, students, guardians, and administration, our goal is to inspire the use of the arts as a meaningful child-centred pedagogy that can incorporate children’s multiple identities and bridge the gap between home and school.\r\n\r\nSimultaneously, a team of artists explored the local art forms of Gatlang to see how we could incorporate art forms that are more familiar to the children and closer to their identities.\r\n\r\nThis is the first of two ArtWorks! trips planned to this majority Tamang community.\r\n\r\nWe see this as a beginning of a longer term relationship.\r\n\r\n<em>Please continue to the Photo Stories and Video for details.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>ArtWorks! <em>Sangai Khelaun</em> is supported by Shikshya Foundation Nepal. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Works with Students</h3>\r\nECD and Class 1: Prathama, Niranjan, Rumi, Sushma, Ichhya: Taking Turns, Setting up Stations\r\n\r\nSunita and Sharareh—Different Mediums of Expression—Class 2: Drawing &amp; Painting our Bodies; Class 3: Creating Stories around Objects, Drawing our Surroundings—exploring possibilities of multilingual education\r\n\r\nAgrim, Merit, and Sugam—Music Education: Tungna, Exploring Music\r\n\r\nShailendra and Dipti—Class 3: Reading and Collage, Class 2: Reading and Drawing\r\n\r\nNischal and music ed group: Class 5—Reading and Reusing Objects-musical instruments, drawing\r\n<h3>Lessons</h3>\r\nDifferent Mediums of Expression\r\n\r\nClass 2: Drawing &amp; Painting our Bodies; Class 3: Creating Stories around Objects, Drawing our Surroundings—exploring possibilities of multilingual education\r\n\r\nClass 2: Reading and Drawing\r\n\r\nMusic Education: Tungna, Exploring Music\r\n\r\nClass 3: Reading and Collage,\r\n\r\nClass 5—Reading and Reusing Objects-musical instruments, drawing\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>New Heading</h3>\r\nCurabitur lacinia orci mi. Donec vel augue nibh. Aliquam at justo ac ante viverra accumsan vitae ac tellus. In mi risus, gravida id justo et, volutpat con Quisque purus mi, pellentesque eget vehicula ac, hendrerit ac lectus. Fusce tortor libero, tempor feugiat libero pulvinar, finibus posuere magna. Morbi sagittis, dolor at placerat.[:ne]fasdfsadfsdaf asdf dfsadasdas[:]', '[:en]ArtWorks! Sangai Khelaun Gatlang, Rasuwa[:ne]projectX[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '159-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-27 13:04:09', '2016-01-27 07:19:09', '', 159, 'http://srijanalaya.org/159-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(572, 2, '2016-01-27 13:45:27', '2016-01-27 08:00:27', '[:en]<h3>Project Description</h3>\r\nOn 5 December, 2015, seven months after the April 25 and May 12 earthquakes, ArtWorks! <em>Sangai Khelaun</em> arrived at Gatlang, Rasuwa with a team of fifteen educators and artists—visual and language artists, dancers, and musicians.\r\n\r\nWe arrived in a majority Tamang village of over 500 households where all the homes were destroyed by the earthquake, and except for a few, people are living in tents in the surrounding fields.  For three days, our team conducted art workshops from ECD to Class 5 at Nepal Rastriya Secondary School’s Temporary Learning Centres.  The school has a little less than three hundred children from ECD to Class 10.  Through the work with the teachers, students, guardians, and administration, our goal is to inspire the use of the arts as a meaningful child-centred pedagogy that can incorporate children’s multiple identities and bridge the gap between home and school.\r\n\r\nSimultaneously, a team of artists explored the local art forms of Gatlang to see how we could incorporate art forms that are more familiar to the children and closer to their identities.\r\n\r\nThis is the first of two ArtWorks! trips planned to this majority Tamang community.\r\n\r\nWe see this as a beginning of a longer term relationship.\r\n\r\n<em>Please continue to the Photo Stories and Video for details.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>ArtWorks! <em>Sangai Khelaun</em> is supported by Shikshya Foundation Nepal. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Lessons</h3>\r\nDifferent Mediums of Expression\r\n\r\nECD and Class 1:\r\n\r\nClass 2: Drawing &amp; Painting our Bodies; Class 3: Creating Stories around Objects, Drawing our Surroundings—exploring possibilities of multilingual education\r\n\r\nClass 2: Reading and Drawing\r\n\r\nMusic Education: Tungna, Exploring Music\r\n\r\nClass 3: Reading and Collage,\r\n\r\nClass 5—Reading and Reusing Objects-musical instruments, drawing\r\n<h